 Here we have $x^2+y^2+1 \ge C(x+y)$ for all $x$ and $y$ and we want to find the largest $C.$ So, we square both sides and take $1$ to the other side, then complete the square. Doing so, we find \[(x+C)^2+(y+C)^2 \ge C^2+C+1.\]Thus, we have
\begin{align*}
C^2+C+1 &\le (x^2+y^2+1),\\
\sqrt{C^2+C+1 } &\le \sqrt{x^2+y^2+1}
\end{align*}But this will always be greater than two, since $x^2+y^2 \ge 0,$ so the maximum $C$ can be is $\boxed{2}.$</think> <answer> $2$</answer>

