response:
Because the route from $A$ to $B$ consists of a sequence of right movements $$R$$ and downward movements $$D$$,we can represent the sequence as a string of the letters $$R$$ and $$D$$. For example, the sequence $$RRDD$$ represents the path $\begin{matrix}A & & & B\\ \downarrow & \\\downarrow & & & B\\ & & & B \end{matrix}$. In this case, the two paths $\begin{matrix}A & & & B\\ \end{matrix}\quad \text{and}\quad \begin{matrix}A & & & B\\ & & & B\\ & \downarrow & & B\\ & & & B \end{matrix} $ are represented by the strings $RRDD$ and $RDRD$, respectively. Since every path from $A$ to $B$ consists of exactly 10 movements, and exactly 5 of them are $$R$$ and 5 of them are $$D$$, the total number of paths from $A$ to $B$ is the number of ways in which we can arrange the letters $$RRRRRDDDD$$. By using the multiplication principle, this number is
$$\text{Number of arrangements of 5$$R$$}\times \text{Number of arrangements of 5$$D$$}
= 10C5 \times 10C5 = 252. $$</think> <answer>252</answer>

solution:
For $r = \sin 2 \theta,$
\begin{align*}
y &= r \sin \theta \\
&= \sin 2 \theta \sin \theta \\
&= 2 \sin^2 \theta \cos \theta \\
&= 2 (1 - \cos^2 \theta) \cos \theta.
\end{align*}Let $k = \cos \theta.$  Then $y = 2 (1 - k^2) k,$ and
\[y^2 = 4k^2 (1 - k^2)^2 = 4k^2 (1 - k^2)(1 - k^2).\]By AM-GM,
\[2k^2 (1 - k^2)(1 - k^2) \le \left( \frac{(2k^2) + (1 - k^2) + (1 - k^2)}{3} \right)^3 = \frac{8}{27},\]so
\[y^2 \le \frac{16}{27}.\]Hence,
\[|y| \le \sqrt{\frac{16}{27}} = \frac{4 \sqrt{3}}{9}.\]We get $y = \boxed{\frac{4 \sqrt{3}}{9}}$ when $k^2 = \cos^2 \theta = \frac{1}{3},$ so this is the maximum $y$-coordinate.

[asy]
unitsize(3 cm);

pair moo (real t) {
  real r = sin(2*t);
  return (r*cos(t), r*sin(t));
}

path foo = moo(0);
real t;

for (t = 0; t <= 2*pi + 0.01; t = t + 0.01) {
  foo = foo--moo(t);
}

draw(foo,red);

draw((-1,0)--(1,0));
draw((0,-1)--(0,1));
draw((-1,4*sqrt(3)/9)--(1,4*sqrt(3)/9),blue);

label("$r = \sin 2 \theta$", (1.2,0.6), red);
label("$y = \frac{4 \sqrt{3}}{9}$", (-1, 4*sqrt(3)/9), W, blue);
[/asy]

