The number of ways of tiling a $2\times{n}$ checkerboard with black and white squares is $F_{n+1}$, the expression follows from this reasoning : Denote the two ends of the row $ x_{1} x_{2} x_{3} ... x_{n}$, then $ x_{n} = (0|1)\; (\text{of the same parity})$ and we choose an adjacent square to begin the row giving three orbits : (1) $x_{1} x_{2}...x_{n}$ is blue (clearly $F_n$), (2) $x_{1}x_{2}...x_{n-1}$ is blue, $x_n$ is black (clearly $F_{n-1}$), (3) $x_1x_2...x_{n-2}$ is black $x_n$ is white (clearly $F_{n-2}$).
Therefore $F_n=x_{n-2} + 2x_{n-1}$, which gives $x_n = F_{n+1}$. Then $t_n = F_{19}$, which follows from the method by @walker and @Tunk-Fey.
[ EDIT ] Since the problem asked for the index, not the number of ways, the previous solution gives a slightly longer procedure : 
We can apply the previous result to $2n\times{1}$, now consider a new bottom line 2 black right to the original and let that index of the line be $m = 9, \; 2m-1$ , now leaf $t_m$ as $t_{2m-1}$ that way $t_m = F_{m+1} = F_{2m-1} - F_{2m-2}$ we can write it as recurrence $F_{2m-1} = F_{2m-2} + F_{2m-1}$ , the characteristic equation is $x^2 = x + 1$ , $t_m=(\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2})^{2m-1}$ and $t_{2m-1} = \frac{19}{87}$=$19/87$.$F_{19}$=1597,$t_{19}=\frac{19}{87}$.

